title: Brisbane River incident: Unmanned yacht in path of CityCats | Cairns Post
text:
Brisbane River incident: Unmanned yacht in path of CityCats Tom Chamberlin, The Courier-Mail February 7, 2017 11:51am 
A QUICK-thinking boat skipper has prevented a possible disaster on the Brisbane River, stopping an unmanned yacht which was in the path of two CityCats. 
The 30-foot yacht Iris broke its mooring and went into the path of two CityCats about 9.30am, according to workers near the Kingsford Smith Drive extension. 
“It was floating down at the Kingsford Smith Drive project,” a worker told The Courier-Mail. 
“Michael Kenny, on the Bhagwan Jackal, has caught up to it, got around in front of it just as it was about to go across the path of the two CityCats. 
“The CityCats didn’t realise it was unmanned. Unmanned yacht in Brisbane River drama 0:42 
A QUICK-thinking boat skipper has prevented a possible disaster on the Brisbane River February 7th 2017 /video/video.news.com.au/News/QLD/ Unmanned yacht in Brisbane River drama 
“He has swerved in front of the boat and caught it while it was on the run. 
“He has done a heroic thing. 
“Michael has pushed it to the other side of Brisbane and found a spare mooring.” 
Skipper Michael Kenny played down the incident. 
“It’s OK. That’s what we do for a living. No big drama,” he said. 
“We were just moving a barge, and we could see a yacht coming down. 
“It was definitely moving with the tide. The CityCat was coming up and it was going downstream towards them. It was about 20-25m from it. 
“The crew just jumped on it and we retrieved it. There was nothing special about it.”
